ADDTEAM: Depression. This topic is somewhat common in my experience working for German companies. I believe this has a great impact on the team performance overall & there aren't really effective methods to handle this properly. Cultural differences. While normally people are very open to this there are from time to time concrete matters that cause disagreements between colleagues. I truly think this is a problem that arises due to our blind beliefs that our culture implants on us. Instead of embracing different ways of working we simply respectfully deny them. I believe in a future when nationalities are irrelevant (this only bias people anyways) and we treat each other as simply complex yet beautiful human beings.

ADDCLIENT: Sometimes client staff won't communicate with the technical team directly but rather only via management channels. However, most of the time communication is still possible via either the resident business experts or informal contacts from previous projects at the same client.
FEEDBACK: It wasn't entirely clear to me whether the questions under "How problematic to the project's success are the factors below? A project is considered successful if it is accepted by the client (even if it has exceeded time or budget constraints)." should take into account how strongly the factors manifest or not.E.g. misunderstandings don't happen all that often in my team so they don't impact the success very much compared to more frequent issues - but the impact of a misunderstanding which slipped through the cracks is higher than of some of these more frequent factors. I went with the latter interpretation when answering.
